# Architecture

Headless Python game loop. Separate admin/offline tools for song authoring. Keep hardware adapters isolated from game logic (follow prototype pattern: `hw/` vs `engine/`).

## Core Runtime Modules

### Game Manager
- Owns the main **update loop** at `runtime.update_hz` from config (default 60 Hz)
- Holds **game state**: health, active notes, hit/miss results, game-over
- Loads all numeric tuning from `toxic_game.toml` — never hardcode gameplay constants
- Orchestrates other managers each frame: poll inputs → advance song time → evaluate hits → update LEDs
- Does **not** talk to hardware directly — delegates to managers

### Song Manager
- Plays the audio file
- Exposes **current playback position** and, on request, **current beat** and **bar**
- Beat/bar derived from song config: BPM + delay-to-first-beat + elapsed playback time
- Single source of truth for musical time during gameplay

### Button Manager
- Returns whether each button was **pressed since the last frame** (edge-triggered, not held state)
- Abstracts GPIO; provide no-op / simulated implementation for dev without hardware
- Reference: `/home/pi/rythm-jump/rythm_jump/hw/gpio_input.py`

### LED Manager
- Renders visuals to the LED strip each frame
- Running lights, brightness ramp, white/red hit flashes
- Abstracts `rpi_ws281x`; provide no-op / in-memory implementation for tests
- Reference: `/home/pi/rythm-jump/rythm_jump/hw/led_output.py`, `engine/led_frames.py`

## Offline / Admin Modules

### Song Configuration (admin tool)
- Run **outside** the game loop
- Inputs: audio file, song name, BPM, delay to first beat
- Produces a song package usable by Song Manager and tap recording
- Not part of the runtime game binary/process

### Tap Recording (admin tool)
- Run **outside** the game loop (or in a dedicated recording mode)
- Plays the song; operator presses buttons at intended beats
- Records inputs, **quantizes to quarter notes (4ths)**
- Output: **tap note file** — plain text, one marker per beat where a player must jump
- File is **human-editable** in a text editor after recording

## Data Flow (runtime)

```
Song Manager (time/beat) ──► Game Manager ◄── Button Manager (presses)
                                    │
                                    ▼
                              LED Manager (frame)
```

## Design Principles

- Managers are **thin adapters** or **focused domain logic** — avoid a god object
- Song data (config + tap notes) is **read-only** during gameplay
- Prefer explicit types and testable pure functions for timing/scoring math
- Reuse proven hardware patterns from `rythm-jump` rather than reinventing GPIO/LED glue
